ntsb4075txt-1-5-5-0-1 This is preliminary information, subject to change, and may contain errors. 
ntsb4075txt-1-5-5-0-2 Any errors in this report will be corrected when the final report has been completed. 
ntsb4075txt-1-5-5-0-3 On May 30, 2001, about 1155 Alaska daylight time, a float-equipped de Havilland DHC-2 airplane, N150PL, sustained substantial damage during a landing on Alexander Creek, about 1.5 miles north-northeast of Alexander, Alaska. 
ntsb4075txt-1-5-5-0-4 The airplane was being operated as a visual flight rules (VFR) local area instructional flight when the accident occurred. 
ntsb4075txt-1-5-5-0-5 The airplane was owned and operated by the private certificated pilot/dual student. 
ntsb4075txt-1-5-5-0-6 The commercial certificated pilot/flight instructor, and the student, were not injured. 
ntsb4075txt-1-5-5-0-7 Visual meteorological conditions prevailed. 
ntsb4075txt-1-5-5-0-8 The flight originated at the Lake Hood Seaplane Base, Anchorage, Alaska, about 1115. 
ntsb4075txt-1-5-5-0-9 During a telephone conversation with the National Transportation Safety Board (NTSB) investigator-in-charge (IIC), on May 31, 2001, the owner/student pilot reported the flight was the second day of instruction, conducted to gain additional experience operating on lakes and rivers in Alaska. 
ntsb4075txt-1-5-5-0-10 After departure from Lake Hood, the student did some aerial maneuvering, and then proceeded to land on Alexander Creek. 
ntsb4075txt-1-5-5-0-11 After touchdown on the creek in a northbound direction, the airplane was decelerating with the water rudders in the up position. 
ntsb4075txt-1-5-5-0-12 The airplane suddenly veered to the right, and the floats collided with the creek bank. 
ntsb4075txt-1-5-5-0-13 The left wing of the airplane collided with trees along the bank, and the propeller struck the bank. 
ntsb4075txt-1-5-5-0-14 In a telephone conversation with the flight instructor on May 31st, he reported that he was providing dual instruction to the already certificated student pilot. 
ntsb4075txt-1-5-5-0-15 The instructor said the touchdown on the creek was normal until the airplane veered to the right. 
ntsb4075txt-1-5-5-0-16 He said he did not know the reason why the airplane veered to the right. 
